<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-823-638  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 823 638.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 3 1990 v7 n35 p66(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Text management's mission: locate what's relevant. (part2)(Applied Intelligence) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Martin, James.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Corporations are beginning to turn their attention on themanagement of textual information, which includes manuals,articles, correspondence and electronic-mail messages.andP;  Textmanagement emphasizes content and addresses the maintenance andretrieval of text.andP;  Since queries of a text database are concernedwith content, a match in a text item does not insure that the textitem is relevant.andP;  A user's objective in doing a search is simple:locate what's relevant.andP;  However, the ways people deal with textare individualized, so text management must present search andretrieval methods that are highly flexible.andP;  Generating user,reference and maintenance manuals with document-assemblytechnology could make certain sections of manuals easier toidentify.andP;  Document-assembly technology facilitates the managementof small portions of text that are used in several documents.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data ManagementInformation Storage and RetrievalText Data BasesSearchingNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The various processes of text management. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>This is the second article in a series on text management and its influencein the corporate environment.andM;In the 1980s the need to manage and retrieve data -- general ledger,purchasing, inventory, order entry, and so on -- was met bydatabase-management systems (DBMSs).andP;  Now that corporations understand howeffectively they can use computerized data, they're turning their attentionto managing textual information.andM;As opposed to data, text comprises memos, E-mail messages, correspondence,manuals, articles and journals.andP;  Text management as illustrated in the figurerefers to the maintenance and retrieval of text and its associated images.andO;It emphasizes the content of the text items, rather than its format orstructure.andM;This emphasis on content is why text management doesn't lend itself totraditional DBMS technology.andP;  DBMS retrieval is oriented to values in recordsand fields that are matched against the query criteria; those that match arereturned.andM;Queries against a text collection are oriented to content.andP;  Words containedin the text items are matched against words used in a search criteria.andP;  Butthat's where the similarity in query capabilities end.andM;A match in a text item does not automatically determine that the text item isrelevant.andP;  If a search phrase appears only once, the retrieved document maybe irrelevant, and users can't afford to spend valuable time sorting throughirrelevant documents.andM;Computerized information systems usually deal with fixed-length data.andO;Information about the data is embedded in the structural design of theapplication, and the rules concerning data manipulation are necessarilyrigid, both to ensure the integrity of the data and to facilitate processing.andM;If the information doesn't fit into the pigeonholes established by thedatabase design, it's often discarded.andP;  This problem can be avoided astext-management systems continue to evolve.andM;Users' objectives when dealing with text seem deceptively straightforward:Locate what's relevant.andM;In reality, this involves many steps and many variations.andP;  One user mightsimply want to browse through the text, another might want to incorporate apiece of a document into a memo or a report, and another might just want tofile an interesting document for later use.andM;In addition, the way people deal with text differs from person to person --there's no standard pattern.andP;  To cope with these differences, text managementmust provide search and retrieval methodologies that are both intelligent andflexible.andM;Consider the following scenario: Your division has been assigned a majorproduct update.andP;  The design and production changes are relativelystraightforward, but revising the associated documentation will requiredisproportionate effort.andM;Is there an effective way to isolate all sections of the reference,maintenance and user manuals that will be affected by the proposedimprovements?andP;  Or will every paragraph on every page need to be checked?andO;What will this additional time cost?andP;  How long will it take?andM;The use of text-management technology could provide methods for efficientlyand effectively handling this seemingly overwhelming task.andP;  If the manualswere in machine-readable form, they could be indexed, and a full-text searchcould be performed using words and phrases that reflect the nature of thechanges.andM;If the reference, maintenance and user manuals were generated usingdocument-assembly technology, the affected sections of those manuals couldeasily be identified.andP;  Document-assembly technology facilitates themanagement of small sections of text that are used in more than one document.andO;The resulting document is generated on demand.andM;Next week I'll discuss the management of the creation of text.andM;----------The concepts in this article are described in a new volume, Text Management,of The James Martin Report Series.andP;  For more information on this volume, call(617) 639-1958.andP;  For information on seminars, contact (in the United Statesand Canada) Technology Transfer Institute, 741 10th St., Santa Monica, Calif.andO;90402 (213) 394-8305.andP;  In Europe, contact Savant, 2 New St., Carnforth,Lancs., LA5 9BX United Kingdom (0524) 734 505.andO;</TEXT></DOC>